It was you.

724
00:59:26,473 --> 00:59:28,839
- You working tomorrow night?
- Yeah.

725
00:59:29,042 --> 00:59:30,976
Why didn't you say anything?

726
00:59:31,177 --> 00:59:35,079
You would've thought
I was crazy or drunk. Or both.

727
00:59:35,315 --> 00:59:37,044
Yeah, but...

728
00:59:37,817 --> 00:59:40,217
..I liked you.
You should have said something.

729
00:59:40,420 --> 00:59:43,287
How? You were with your boyfriend.

730
00:59:43,490 --> 00:59:46,391
You know what? Excuses, excuses.
You are a coward.

731
00:59:46,593 --> 00:59:48,493
I'm not a coward.

732
00:59:48,695 --> 00:59:52,597
Oh, really?
Well, what about your girlfriend?

733
00:59:53,099 --> 00:59:54,930
What? I told you already...

734
00:59:55,168 --> 00:59:58,296
..she's not my girlfriend.
- He's not my boyfriend either.

735
00:59:58,538 --> 01:00:02,201
Oh, really? Well, what is he, then?
Your brother?

736
01:00:03,076 --> 01:00:08,013
We have a comedian. What'd you have,
a clown for breakfast this morning?

737
01:00:09,683 --> 01:00:11,742
Wonderful. Our first fight.

738
01:00:11,951 --> 01:00:15,910
You could write a song about it
and go sing it in San Francisco.

739
01:00:20,193 --> 01:00:21,956
What?

740
01:00:22,362 --> 01:00:23,829
Hello.

741
01:00:24,030 --> 01:00:25,964
Hey, Henry.

742
01:00:27,400 --> 01:00:28,731
What?

743
01:00:28,902 --> 01:00:30,767
You'll let me know if you need anything?

744
01:00:30,970 --> 01:00:32,767
Yes, I will.

745
01:00:34,107 --> 01:00:35,096
- Hi.
- Good afternoon.

746
01:00:35,342 --> 01:00:39,073
I'm looking for my father. I don't know
which room he's in. Simon Wyler?

747
01:00:39,279 --> 01:00:42,077
- Mr. Wyler, the architect?
- Yes.

748
01:00:42,282 --> 01:00:45,410
I'm Anna Klyczynski.
I'm the Attending for your father.

749
01:00:45,618 --> 01:00:47,779
Hey. What happened? How is he?

750
01:00:47,987 --> 01:00:52,481
He's okay. He's had a heart attack.
Fortunately, relatively minor.

751
01:00:52,726 --> 01:00:55,889
His vitals are fine and he's stable...

752
01:00:56,062 --> 01:00:58,155
..but it will require an intervention.

753
01:00:58,398 --> 01:01:01,424
He's agreed to schedule it
for tomorrow.

754
01:01:16,449 --> 01:01:19,145
Good to see you're taking it easy.

755
01:01:19,953 --> 01:01:24,014
Well, you... You didn't need to come.
I'm perfectly well.

756
01:01:24,391 --> 01:01:26,450
Perfectly all right.

757
01:01:26,659 --> 01:01:29,093
Well, you had a heart attack, Dad.

758
01:01:29,295 --> 01:01:32,628
I had an episode, for chrissake.

759
01:01:32,832 --> 01:01:34,766
Nothing more.

760
01:01:35,468 --> 01:01:38,801
Appreciate it if you kept everything
in its perspective.

761
01:01:41,007 --> 01:01:44,408
Well then, I just wanna let you know
I'm here if you need anything.

762
01:01:46,546 --> 01:01:48,343
Coffee.

763
01:01:48,782 --> 01:01:50,477
What?

764
01:01:50,917 --> 01:01:52,714
You heard me.

765
01:01:55,121 --> 01:01:56,952
Coffee.

766
01:01:58,792 --> 01:02:01,022
<i>There's something
I never told you, Kate.</i>

767
01:02:01,227 --> 01:02:03,695
<i>You see, it was my father
who built the lake house.</i>

768
01:02:03,930 --> 01:02:06,956
<i>I mean, with his own hands.</i>

769
01:02:07,167 --> 01:02:10,000
<i>And it was a long time ago,
before he was famous...</i>

770
01:02:10,203 --> 01:02:13,434
<i>...when he still had a family
and worshipped my mother.</i>

771
01:02:13,640 --> 01:02:17,440
<i>Her name was Mary,
and the house was a gift for her.</i>

772
01:02:17,644 --> 01:02:20,477
<i>She was smart and funny.</i>

773
01:02:20,680 --> 01:02:24,343
<i>She could have done anything, but chose
to take care of my brother and I...</i>

774
01:02:24,551 --> 01:02:26,348
<i>...and help him build his career.</i>

775
01:02:26,553 --> 01:02:30,580
<i>You see, the more successful he became,
the more impossible he was to live with.</i>

776
01:02:30,824 --> 01:02:34,385
<i>Finally, she just couldn't take
living with him anymore.</i>

777
01:02:34,594 --> 01:02:37,529
<i>She left him.</i>

778
01:02:37,730 --> 01:02:39,857
<i>Within a year, she got sick.</i>

779
01:02:40,066 --> 01:02:43,729
<i>Unfortunately, she never learned
how to stop loving him.</i>

780
01:02:44,971 --> 01:02:47,371
<i>He wasn't at the funeral.</i>

781
01:02:48,708 --> 01:02:50,972
<i>When I asked him why...</i>

782
01:02:56,716 --> 01:02:59,514
Go on, Alex. What did he say?

783
01:03:03,490 --> 01:03:07,221
He said, "She was dead to me the
moment she stepped out of the house. "

784
01:03:10,230 --> 01:03:14,530
And then he gave me
one of his architect-of-the-year grins.

785
01:03:29,549 --> 01:03:30,811
I hope you appreciate this.

786
01:03:31,050 --> 01:03:33,780
I had to sneak past
three nurses and your Attending.

787
01:03:34,020 --> 01:03:36,318
Oh, jeez, it's hot.

788
01:03:36,656 --> 01:03:38,055
It's not decaf, is it?

789
01:03:38,258 --> 01:03:40,123
It should be, but it isn't.

790
01:03:43,830 --> 01:03:46,458
That's not bad. Thank you...

791
01:03:46,666 --> 01:03:48,293
..son.

792
01:03:48,535 --> 01:03:51,629
- You're welcome.
- Where's your brother?

793
01:03:51,804 --> 01:03:53,931
I sent him away.
He wasn't feeling well.

794
01:03:54,140 --> 01:03:57,041
- You know how he is, he worries.
- Yeah, I know.

795
01:03:57,243 --> 01:03:59,336
He gets that from your mother,
I'm afraid.

796
01:04:00,113 --> 01:04:01,580
She always worried too much.

797
01:04:01,781 --> 01:04:03,476
What are you looking at?

798
01:04:04,284 --> 01:04:06,081
Oh, yeah, here, take a gander.

799
01:04:06,286 --> 01:04:09,653
It's a proposal for a museum.

800
01:04:09,856 --> 01:04:13,053
- Who is it?
- Someone new.

801
01:04:13,960 --> 01:04:17,259
Oh, I like the walkways,
where the light falls.

802
01:04:17,463 --> 01:04:19,090
What are the materials?

803
01:04:19,499 --> 01:04:21,490
Granite. Aluminum.

804
01:04:21,701 --> 01:04:24,169
White panels
are straight out of Meier...

805
01:04:24,370 --> 01:04:28,704
..but the interior color coming through
the front windows, that's different.

806
01:04:29,542 --> 01:04:32,875
It's not new,
but it's clean, uncluttered.

807
01:04:33,112 --> 01:04:34,807
I like it.

808
01:04:35,381 --> 01:04:38,441
When was the last time
you were in Barcelona?

809
01:04:40,219 --> 01:04:42,687
Years ago, with you, Mom and Henry.

810
01:04:42,889 --> 01:04:45,517
Do you remember visiting
Casa de la Caritat?

811
01:04:46,693 --> 01:04:48,320
The almshouse.

812
01:04:48,528 --> 01:04:50,996
That's right. You mentioned Meier.

813
01:04:51,197 --> 01:04:56,100
His Barcelona museum stands
in the same area as Casa de la Caritat.

814
01:04:56,302 --> 01:04:58,293
It drinks the same light.

815
01:04:58,504 --> 01:05:03,407
Meier designed a series of louvered
skylights to capture that light...

816
01:05:03,643 --> 01:05:08,410
..and cast it inward to illuminate
the art within, but indirectly.

817
01:05:08,648 --> 01:05:13,642
And that was important,
because although light enhances art...

818
01:05:13,853 --> 01:05:18,654
..it can also degrade it. But you know
all that already, you son of a gun.

819
01:05:18,825 --> 01:05:20,725
Now, this...

820
01:05:22,662 --> 01:05:24,687
..where do you suppose
this is to be built?

821
01:05:24,864 --> 01:05:25,922
I have no idea.

822
01:05:26,099 --> 01:05:28,533
- Oh, but you said you liked it.
- Conceptually.

823
01:05:28,701 --> 01:05:30,931
Now, come on.

824
01:05:31,170 --> 01:05:33,832
You know as well as I do
that the light in Barcelona...

825
01:05:34,040 --> 01:05:36,406
..is quite different
from the light in Tokyo.

826
01:05:36,576 --> 01:05:39,670
And the light in Tokyo
is different from that in Prague.

827
01:05:39,879 --> 01:05:45,875
A truly great structure, one that
is meant to stand the tests of time...

828
01:05:46,085 --> 01:05:48,576
..never disregards its environment.

829
01:05:48,788 --> 01:05:50,585
An architect takes that into account.

830
01:05:50,790 --> 01:05:55,523
He knows that if he wants presence,
he must consult with nature.

831
01:05:55,728 --> 01:06:00,131
He must be captivated by the light.

832
01:06:00,299 --> 01:06:04,030
Always the light. Always.

833
01:06:59,625 --> 01:07:01,923
Hey. I have an emergency.
Take my shift. Please.

834
01:07:06,933 --> 01:07:08,457
Hello.

835
01:07:08,668 --> 01:07:11,296
<i>- Mr. Wyler?
- Yes.</i>

836
01:07:11,504 --> 01:07:14,701
<i>This is Dr. Klyczynski
at Chicago City Hospital.</i>

837
01:07:15,441 --> 01:07:18,933
<i>I'm afraid I have some
difficult news for you.</i>

838
01:07:21,748 --> 01:07:24,308
<i>I'm so sorry, Alex.</i>

839
01:07:25,551 --> 01:07:28,645
<i>I wish somehow
I could be there with you...</i>

840
01:07:29,188 --> 01:07:32,885
<i>...that we could sit together and look
out over the water and the light...</i>

841
01:07:33,126 --> 01:07:36,027
<i>...in this house your father built.</i>

842
01:07:39,031 --> 01:07:41,898
<i>I could be a shoulder for you
like you've been for me.</i>

843
01:07:42,135 --> 01:07:45,263
<i>And tell you that
everything is gonna be okay.</i>

844
01:07:47,173 --> 01:07:50,006
<i>If I could do one thing for you today...</i>

845
01:07:50,209 --> 01:07:52,268
<i>...from here...</i>

846
01:07:52,478 --> 01:07:56,073
<i>...one small, simple thing
from the future...</i>

847
01:07:56,682 --> 01:07:58,673
<i>...I hope this is it.</i>

848
01:08:00,086 --> 01:08:02,816
<i>It won't be published
for a couple of years...</i>

849
01:08:03,022 --> 01:08:05,684
<i>...but I don't think
you should have to wait that long.</i>

850
01:08:07,393 --> 01:08:10,362
<i>I hope it helps you know
how much you were loved.</i>

851
01:09:54,800 --> 01:09:57,200
Pick a place. I'll be there, I promise.

852
01:09:57,436 --> 01:09:58,767
Tomorrow, what do you say?

853
01:09:58,971 --> 01:10:00,802
But, Alex,
it won't be tomorrow for you.

854
01:10:01,007 --> 01:10:04,408
- You're gonna have to wait two years.
- I know, I don't care. I'll wait.

855
01:10:04,610 --> 01:10:05,941
Are you sure? I don't know.

856
01:10:06,145 --> 01:10:08,613
I do. I've never been so sure
of anything in my life.

857
01:10:08,814 --> 01:10:11,942
Okay. I'll see you in two years, then.

858
01:10:12,151 --> 01:10:14,415
See you tomorrow, then.

859
01:10:14,820 --> 01:10:16,515
Kate...

860
01:10:16,722 --> 01:10:18,713
..where would you like to go?

861
01:10:21,527 --> 01:10:23,188
II Mare.

862
01:10:23,362 --> 01:10:25,353
When were you hoping
to dine with us?

863
01:10:25,564 --> 01:10:27,156
Two years from tomorrow.

864
01:10:27,366 --> 01:10:29,527
- Two years from tomorrow?
- Yeah.

865
01:10:29,735 --> 01:10:31,703
- Two years?
- From tomorrow.

866
01:10:33,673 --> 01:10:35,664
- Hi.
- Hello. Name?

867
01:10:35,841 --> 01:10:36,967
Forster.

868
01:10:37,143 --> 01:10:38,508
- Can I have your name?
- Wyler.

869
01:10:38,678 --> 01:10:41,238
Or Wyler, I'm...
I'm really not sure.

870
01:10:41,414 --> 01:10:43,644
I think we should be able
to accommodate you.

871
01:10:43,849 --> 01:10:44,907
- Great.
- Wyler?

872
01:10:47,086 --> 01:10:48,576
Wyler.

873
01:10:50,222 --> 01:10:52,690
Your waiter will be right with you.

874
01:11:16,849 --> 01:11:19,010
Good evening, miss.

875
01:11:20,686 --> 01:11:23,120
Complimentary.

876
01:11:33,399 --> 01:11:36,232
- Thank you.
- Good luck.

877
01:11:58,891 --> 01:12:01,257
Another glass for the lady?

878
01:13:28,914 --> 01:13:31,007
<i>You weren't there.</i>

879
01:13:31,350 --> 01:13:33,545
<i>You didn't come.</i>

880
01:13:39,925 --> 01:13:41,722
I don't understand.

881
01:13:41,927 --> 01:13:45,055
<i>Something must have happened.
I'm sorry.</i>

882
01:13:45,264 --> 01:13:48,131
<i>I've got two years, Kate.
We can try again.</i>

883
01:13:48,334 --> 01:13:52,566
<i>No, Alex, it's too late.</i>

884
01:13:52,771 --> 01:13:56,366
<i>It already happened. It didn't work.</i>

885
01:13:56,575 --> 01:13:58,509
<i>Don't give up on me, Kate.</i>

886
01:13:58,711 --> 01:14:02,408
<i>What about Persuasion?
You told me. They wait.</i>

887
01:14:02,648 --> 01:14:04,673
<i>They meet again,
they have another chance.</i>

888
01:14:04,884 --> 01:14:07,011
<i>Life is not a book, Alex.</i>

889
01:14:07,219 --> 01:14:09,710
<i>And it can be over in a second.</i>

890
01:14:09,922 --> 01:14:13,289
<i>I was having lunch with my mother
at Daley Plaza...</i>

891
01:14:13,526 --> 01:14:16,256
<i>...and a man was killed
right in front of me.</i>

892
01:14:16,462 --> 01:14:18,692
<i>He died in my arms.</i>

893
01:14:18,898 --> 01:14:20,422
<i>And I thought:</i>

894
01:14:20,666 --> 01:14:24,932
<i>"It can't end just like that
on Valentine's Day. "</i>

895
01:14:25,871 --> 01:14:28,863
<i>I thought about all the people
who love him, waiting at home...</i>

896
01:14:29,074 --> 01:14:31,565
<i>...who will never see him again.</i>

897
01:14:32,478 --> 01:14:34,412
<i>And then I thought:</i>

898
01:14:34,613 --> 01:14:36,945
<i>"What if there is no one?"</i>

899
01:14:37,750 --> 01:14:43,245
<i>What if you live your whole life
and no one is waiting?</i>

900
01:14:43,756 --> 01:14:47,692
<i>So I drove to the lake house
looking for any kind of answer.</i>

901
01:14:47,893 --> 01:14:50,293
<i>And I found you.</i>

902
01:14:50,496 --> 01:14:52,930
<i>And I let myself get lost.</i>

903
01:14:53,132 --> 01:14:58,502
<i>Lost in this beautiful fantasy
where time stood still.</i>

904
01:14:58,971 --> 01:15:01,337
<i>But it's not real, Alex.</i>

905
01:15:01,574 --> 01:15:06,511
<i>I have to learn to live
the life that I have got.</i>

906
01:15:08,113 --> 01:15:10,308
<i>Please don't write anymore.</i>

907
01:15:10,516 --> 01:15:12,814
<i>Don't try to find me.</i>

908
01:15:13,752 --> 01:15:16,414
<i>Let me let you go.</i>

909
01:16:03,802 --> 01:16:05,633
Hello.

910
01:16:06,405 --> 01:16:09,340
What? Sorry, hold on.
I can't hear you. I'll be back, sorry.

911
01:16:09,541 --> 01:16:12,203
Hello. Hold on. Hold on.

912
01:16:12,645 --> 01:16:14,340
Hello.

913
01:16:16,882 --> 01:16:18,645
Hi.

914
01:16:24,189 --> 01:16:26,384
How long are you here?

915
01:16:29,595 --> 01:16:32,928
- I'm at a bar with some friends.
- Come.

916
01:16:33,165 --> 01:16:35,725
Well, don't get too excited.

917
01:16:37,169 --> 01:16:39,729
I find that hard to believe.

918
01:16:41,707 --> 01:16:43,174
It is good.

919
01:16:43,375 --> 01:16:46,367
And it was really good
to hear your voice.

920
01:16:46,578 --> 01:16:49,911
I was surprised how good
it was to hear your voice.

921
01:16:53,052 --> 01:16:54,542
So how was your meeting?

922
01:16:54,753 --> 01:16:56,880
- It was good.
- Yeah?

923
01:16:57,089 --> 01:16:59,922
Yeah, I... I got the job.

924
01:17:00,125 --> 01:17:02,457
- Really?
- Yeah.

925
01:17:02,895 --> 01:17:05,056
- Well, congratulations.
- Imagine that.

926
01:17:05,264 --> 01:17:10,896
Yeah. A telecom company.
I'll be in-house counsel. Pays well.

927
01:17:11,103 --> 01:17:13,196
And it's here...

928
01:17:13,405 --> 01:17:14,872
..in Chicago.

929
01:17:15,708 --> 01:17:17,437
Well...

930
01:17:17,643 --> 01:17:19,736
..it's great news.

931
01:17:22,114 --> 01:17:23,911
Hey.

932
01:17:27,886 --> 01:17:29,581
What?

933
01:17:49,775 --> 01:17:51,265
Jack.

934
01:17:51,477 --> 01:17:53,411
Hey, Jack.

935
01:17:53,746 --> 01:17:55,509
Jack.

936
01:19:15,961 --> 01:19:18,225
Are you gonna
come down this weekend?

937
01:19:20,399 --> 01:19:22,594
Don't you miss me a little bit?

938
01:19:23,268 --> 01:19:25,736
Oh, just a little bit. Not a lot, huh?

939
01:19:26,205 --> 01:19:29,868
Okay. No, I heard you. Yeah.

940
01:19:31,743 --> 01:19:35,008
Kate, I'm gonna
have to call you back, okay?

941
01:19:49,862 --> 01:19:52,296
Still wanna rent a lake house?

942
01:19:53,232 --> 01:19:55,564
It's what Kate wants.

943
01:19:55,767 --> 01:19:58,361
How the hell do you know
what Kate wants?

944
01:19:59,738 --> 01:20:01,399
Trust me.

945
01:20:13,285 --> 01:20:16,413
Hey, you. I know you.

946
01:20:22,761 --> 01:20:25,457
Whatever you want out back.

947
01:20:55,360 --> 01:20:57,191
What do you think?

948
01:20:57,796 --> 01:20:59,923
You're fixating. You know?

949
01:21:00,966 --> 01:21:02,797
Why do you keep
tweaking the lake house?

950
01:21:03,001 --> 01:21:05,094
Why don't you do your own work?

951
01:21:05,270 --> 01:21:07,500
Because it's hers.

952
01:21:07,873 --> 01:21:13,140
You're talking about the girl
from the future.

953
01:21:13,345 --> 01:21:15,006
Kate.

954
01:21:15,847 --> 01:21:18,611
And you're still writing with Kate?

955
01:21:18,984 --> 01:21:22,351
- No.
- Why not?

956
01:21:23,822 --> 01:21:25,380
She asked me not to.

957
01:21:26,091 --> 01:21:27,786
Why?

958
01:21:30,095 --> 01:21:31,790
Time.

959
01:21:35,701 --> 01:21:37,225
Hey, come on.

960
01:21:37,469 --> 01:21:41,200
This is a good thing.
You know, you need a real woman.

961
01:21:41,406 --> 01:21:44,500
- A woman...
- Henry, listen.

962
01:21:45,711 --> 01:21:47,508
Listen to me.

963
01:21:47,980 --> 01:21:52,974
While it lasted, she was
more real to me than any of that stuff.

964
01:21:53,185 --> 01:21:57,315
She was more real to me
than anything I've ever known.

965
01:21:59,524 --> 01:22:01,355
I saw her.

966
01:22:02,227 --> 01:22:04,058
I kissed her.

967
01:22:06,431 --> 01:22:08,058
I love her.

968
01:22:11,236 --> 01:22:13,329
And now she's gone.

969
01:22:22,247 --> 01:22:24,010
She's gone.

970
01:22:31,423 --> 01:22:33,050
<i>And Duckett squirts through.</i>

971
01:22:33,558 --> 01:22:35,253
<i>First thing...</i>

972
01:22:36,795 --> 01:22:39,161
<i>How could the Ab Scissor
four-minute ab machine...?</i>

973
01:22:39,364 --> 01:22:42,026
<i>- and your potatoes
cooking on the top.</i>

974
01:22:42,234 --> 01:22:45,795
<i>It's nice out here. Let's stay here.</i>

975
01:22:46,038 --> 01:22:47,903
<i>But we have to eat.</i>

976
01:22:48,907 --> 01:22:52,104
<i>We can eat here. I'll cook.</i>

977
01:22:52,477 --> 01:22:54,741
<i>I thought you didn't like to cook.</i>

978
01:22:55,380 --> 01:22:57,678
<i>No, I don't like to cook.</i>

979
01:22:59,317 --> 01:23:02,616
<i>But I have a chicken in the icebox,
and you're eating it.</i>

980
01:23:02,821 --> 01:23:04,948
<i>What about all
the washing-up afterward?</i>

981
01:23:05,190 --> 01:23:07,750
<i>- We'll eat with our fingers.
- Could you turn that down?</i>

982
01:23:07,959 --> 01:23:09,392
<i>Don't we need any plates?</i>

983
01:23:09,594 --> 01:23:13,291
<i>Yes. One for you,
and one for...</i>

984
01:24:24,903 --> 01:24:28,339
"There could have been
no two hearts so open...

985
01:24:29,007 --> 01:24:31,805
..no tastes so similar...

986
01:24:33,011 --> 01:24:35,912
..no feelings so in unison. "

987
01:24:50,495 --> 01:24:55,330
Ten, nine, eight, seven, six...

988
01:24:55,534 --> 01:25:00,028
..five, four, three, two, one.

989
01:25:00,238 --> 01:25:03,105
Happy New Year!

990
01:25:15,687 --> 01:25:17,450
Come in.

991
01:25:32,337 --> 01:25:33,964
Hi.

992
01:25:34,472 --> 01:25:35,962
Hi.

993
01:25:37,475 --> 01:25:38,908
What do you think?

994
01:25:39,110 --> 01:25:40,975
This is what I gave up lunch for?

995
01:25:41,213 --> 01:25:45,946
- I know it needs work.
- Work? How about a wrecking ball?

996
01:25:46,251 --> 01:25:49,277
I found an architect
who specializes in renovations.

997
01:25:49,487 --> 01:25:51,921
I made an appointment for tomorrow.

998
01:25:56,428 --> 01:25:57,986
Ambush.

999
01:25:58,230 --> 01:25:59,492
Come on.

1000
01:25:59,731 --> 01:26:03,223
We can't stay in my apartment.
We've been there over a year.

1001
01:26:04,369 --> 01:26:06,098
I wanna keep moving forward.

1002
01:26:16,681 --> 01:26:19,980
- It's a new firm.
- "New" as in inexperienced?

1003
01:26:20,185 --> 01:26:22,949
No. "New" as in cheap.

1004
01:26:33,164 --> 01:26:35,530
Hi, Dr. Forster.
We'll be with you in a moment.

1005
01:26:35,767 --> 01:26:37,462
Great, thank you.

1006
01:26:51,216 --> 01:26:54,310
Oh, by the way...

1007
01:26:55,720 --> 01:26:57,847
..happy Valentine's Day.

1008
01:26:58,056 --> 01:27:01,184
Oh, God, Katie,
I didn't get you anything.

1009
01:27:01,426 --> 01:27:04,554
I'm sorry. I've just been
so swamped and...

1010
01:27:04,796 --> 01:27:06,696
Doesn't matter.

1011
01:27:23,214 --> 01:27:26,980
- What is this?
- It's global warming.

1012
01:27:29,220 --> 01:27:33,213
Dr. Forster?
Hi, I'm sorry to have kept you waiting.

1013
01:27:52,010 --> 01:27:54,444
- Hi. Good to see you again.
- Dr. Forster. You too.

1014
01:27:54,679 --> 01:27:57,580
- Hi, I'm Morgan.
- Hey, Morgan. Vanessa Vanderbeck.

1015
01:27:57,782 --> 01:28:02,082
So obviously, the first thing you see
is what we had talked about. The atrium.

1016
01:28:02,787 --> 01:28:04,186
That's stunning.

1017
01:28:04,356 --> 01:28:07,883
So we were able to do it with all
the glass panels in the metal structure?

1018
01:28:08,093 --> 01:28:09,685
- Yeah.
- Can I...?

1019
01:28:09,961 --> 01:28:11,258
Wanna get a beer after work?

1020
01:28:11,496 --> 01:28:15,557
I'm sorry, I can't. I'm taking
Vanessa out for Valentine's Day.

1021
01:28:19,270 --> 01:28:20,760
Wait.

1022
01:28:21,306 --> 01:28:22,739
Say that again.

1023
01:28:22,941 --> 01:28:26,069
It's Valentine's Day today.
I'm taking out Vanessa, my girlfriend.

1024
01:28:26,277 --> 01:28:29,644
Cold champagne, some oysters,
maybe a little chocolate.

1025
01:28:29,881 --> 01:28:33,373
- What's the date?
- It's February 14th.

1026
01:28:34,285 --> 01:28:38,551
- February 14th, 2006.
- Yeah.

1027
01:28:39,157 --> 01:28:42,024
- Stunning. Thank you so much.
- Our pleasure.

1028
01:28:42,227 --> 01:28:44,661
Thank you. Henry will
make sure you have everything.

1029
01:28:44,896 --> 01:28:46,796
Great. They were absolutely beautiful.

1030
01:28:47,032 --> 01:28:48,522
Thank you.

1031
01:28:49,801 --> 01:28:51,291
What?

1032
01:28:52,771 --> 01:28:56,070
Katie, I gotta get back to work.

1033
01:28:59,044 --> 01:29:00,909
Who did this drawing?

1034
01:29:01,112 --> 01:29:03,239
My brother did, actually.

1035
01:29:03,415 --> 01:29:04,780
Who's your brother?

1036
01:29:04,983 --> 01:29:06,974
Alex Wyler.

1037
01:29:07,285 --> 01:29:09,048
Did you know him?

1038
01:29:11,189 --> 01:29:12,747
Yeah.

1039
01:29:13,691 --> 01:29:15,454
Yeah, I know him.

1040
01:29:17,962 --> 01:29:20,157
Do you know how
I can get in touch with him?

1041
01:29:20,365 --> 01:29:23,266
Is he...?
Is he anywhere that I can?

1042
01:29:25,970 --> 01:29:27,835
I'm sorry.

1043
01:29:28,473 --> 01:29:32,500
He died...

1044
01:29:32,977 --> 01:29:35,673
..two years ago today, actually.

1045
01:29:38,983 --> 01:29:41,076
There was an accident.

1046
01:29:58,736 --> 01:30:00,328
Where?

1047
01:30:04,008 --> 01:30:05,498
Kate.

1048
01:30:07,879 --> 01:30:10,313
Wait, just stop. Just stop.

1049
01:30:10,815 --> 01:30:12,908
Goddamn it, answer me.

1050
01:30:13,218 --> 01:30:17,245
What is the matter? Kate.

1051
01:30:19,924 --> 01:30:21,482
Kate!

1052
01:31:25,924 --> 01:31:28,950
Sixty degrees on Valentine's Day.

1053
01:31:29,194 --> 01:31:31,492
This cannot be Chicago.

1054
01:31:31,896 --> 01:31:34,922
The TV says it's global warming.

1055
01:31:35,300 --> 01:31:37,063
Nothing wrong with that.

1056
01:31:37,268 --> 01:31:38,997
It's a dangerous thing.

1057
01:31:39,437 --> 01:31:41,132
<i>Alex...</i>

1058
01:31:42,574 --> 01:31:45,475
<i>...I know why you
didn't show up that night.</i>

1059
01:31:45,710 --> 01:31:48,975
<i>It was you at Daley Plaza that day.</i>

1060
01:31:50,148 --> 01:31:51,945
<i>It was you.</i>

1061
01:31:52,850 --> 01:31:54,909
<i>Please, don't go.</i>

1062
01:31:55,987 --> 01:31:59,445
<i>Just wait. Please.</i>

1063
01:32:00,425 --> 01:32:01,790
<i>Don't look for me.</i>

1064
01:32:01,993 --> 01:32:04,325
<i>Don't try to find me.</i>

1065
01:32:06,497 --> 01:32:08,362
<i>I love you.</i>

1066
01:32:11,202 --> 01:32:14,831
<i>And it's taken me all this time
to say it, but I love you.</i>

1067
01:32:22,347 --> 01:32:23,974
<i>And if you still care for me...</i>

1068
01:32:25,850 --> 01:32:27,784
<i>...wait for me.</i>

1069
01:32:28,319 --> 01:32:30,310
<i>Wait with me.</i>

1070
01:32:30,521 --> 01:32:34,013
<i>Just wait. Wait.</i>

1071
01:32:42,767 --> 01:32:45,167
<i>Wait two years, Alex.</i>

1072
01:32:45,637 --> 01:32:47,969
<i>Come to the lake house.</i>

1073
01:32:48,339 --> 01:32:50,170
<i>I'm here.</i>

1074
01:33:47,365 --> 01:33:49,196
You waited.

